	<table id="questions_table" border=0>
	<tr><td><div class="number">&nbsp;1.</div></td><td>
	<div>When dealing with multiple-choice questions, the key is to...<br>
	

	<span style="width: 20px">a.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">start by discarding the clearly wrong answers</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">b.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">see whether there are answers that don't make sense</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">c.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">underline the differences between answers</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">d.</span><span class="right" style="width: 700px;">find the best answer</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">e.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">find the answer that is closer to the textbook explanation</span>


	</div></td></tr>
	<tr><td><div class="number">&nbsp;2.</div></td><td>
	<div>For multiple-choice questions, the presentation recommends that you...<br>

	<span style="width: 20px">a.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">start by contrasting all the answers with the question</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">b.</span><span class="right" style="width: 700px;">answer the question in your mind first</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">c.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">avoid getting lost in the details</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">d.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">look for action verbs and underline them</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">e.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">circle all the adjectives and compare the answers</span>
	</div></td></tr>
	<tr><td><div class="number">&nbsp;3.</div></td><td>
	<div>One way to approach multiple-choice questions, is to...<br>
	<span style="width: 20px">a.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">choose the questions with absolutes</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">b.</span><span class="right" style="width: 700px;">look for equally plausible options</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">c.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">avoid the global option</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">d.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">choose the most specific answer</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">e.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">look for the most detailed answer</span>
	</div></td></tr>

	<tr><td><div class="number">&nbsp;4.</div></td><td>
	<div>Where should you look for important information like priority or negative polarity?<br>
	<span style="width: 20px">a.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">in the introduction to the question</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">b.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">in the use of verbs in the answer</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">c.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">within the key concepts in the question</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">d.</span><span class="right" style="width: 700px;">in the stem of the answer</span>
	<span style="width: 20px">e.</span><span class="wrong" style="width: 700px;">between the answers</span>
	</div></td></tr>
	</table>


